In this article, President Obama condemns North Korea's launch of a Taepo-dong 2 missile, stating that it violates United Nations Security Council Resolution 1718. He emphasizes the threat posed by North Korea's development and proliferation of ballistic missile technology to the northeast Asian region and international peace and security. The President calls for consultations with allies in the region, such as Japan and South Korea, as well as the U.N. Security Council to address this issue. He urges North Korea to abide by the resolutions of the U.N. Security Council and refrain from further provocative actions. The President also emphasizes the importance of preventing the proliferation of weapons of mass destruction and their means of delivery, while expressing his commitment to maintaining security and stability in northeast Asia. He reiterates the goal of achieving the verifiable denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula through the Six-Party Talks. The President states that North Korea can gain acceptance in the international community if it abandons its pursuit of weapons of mass destruction and complies with its international obligations and commitments.